Note:
==============================================================================
POST-QUANTUM NTT FOUNDATION + SHAKE XOF + COMMON UTILITIES
==============================================================================

Implements the shared Number-Theoretic Transform primitives required by
ML-KEM (FIPS 203) and ML-DSA (FIPS 204), plus SHAKE128/SHAKE256 extendable
output functions which both schemes use for matrix expansion and CBD/uniform
sampling.

Two NTT parameter sets live here, picked at the call site:

  - KYBER : n = 256, q = 3329       (FIPS 203)
  - DILITHIUM : n = 256, q = 8380417 (FIPS 204)

The NTT layer transforms a polynomial f(X) in R_q = Z_q[X]/(X^256+1) into
the NTT domain where multiplication is pointwise (base-multiplied) instead
of a convolution. For Kyber, the cyclotomic X^256+1 factors into 128
quadratic terms (X^2 - zeta) -- so the "NTT" output has 256 coefficients
representing 128 elements of F_q[X]/(X^2 - zeta) and base multiplication
operates on those pairs. For Dilithium, q = 8380417 admits a primitive
512-th root of unity so X^256+1 splits completely into 256 linear factors
and base multiplication is fully pointwise.

All routines are constant-time with respect to coefficients: there are no
data-dependent branches inside any per-coefficient loop and the
Barrett/Montgomery reductions use only arithmetic.

This module also provides:
  - shake128_absorb / shake128_squeeze
  - shake256_absorb / shake256_squeeze
  - shake_state_create / shake_state_destroy helpers
  - barrett_reduce_kyber, montgomery_reduce_kyber
  - barrett_reduce_dilithium, montgomery_reduce_dilithium
  - kyber_compress / kyber_decompress (used by ML-KEM ByteEncode/Decode)
  - byte encoding for variable bit-widths d in [1..12] (Kyber) and [1..23]
    (Dilithium)
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "runtime/core/memory/arena.runa" as Arena
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/sha3.runa" as Sha3

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Constant accessors (Runa bootstrap does not use module-level Constants
Note: for cross-module use; these helpers expose the parameter values as
Note: callable processes so other PQ modules can pull them.)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "ntt_kyber_q" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Kyber modulus q = 3329 from FIPS 203 section 2.4.1.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Returns the prime constant 3329 used as the coefficient modulus throughout
    ML-KEM.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Inlinable: a single constant return.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    No secret material; safe to call from any context.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return 3329
End Process

Process called "ntt_kyber_n" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Kyber polynomial degree n = 256 (FIPS 203 section 2.4.1).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Returns the ring dimension 256 used by all ML-KEM parameter sets.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant return.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Public parameter.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return 256
End Process

Process called "ntt_dilithium_q" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Dilithium modulus q = 8380417 = 2^23 - 2^13 + 1 (FIPS 204 section 2.5.1).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Returns the prime constant 8380417 used as the coefficient modulus
    throughout ML-DSA.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant return.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Public parameter.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return 8380417
End Process

Process called "ntt_dilithium_n" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Dilithium polynomial degree n = 256 (FIPS 204 section 2.5.1).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Returns the ring dimension 256 used by all ML-DSA parameter sets.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant return.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Public parameter.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return 256
End Process

Process called "ntt_kyber_qinv" returns Integer:
    Note: q^{-1} mod 2^16 = 62209 (used by Montgomery reduction)
    Return 62209
End Process

Process called "ntt_dilithium_qinv" returns Integer:
    Note: q^{-1} mod 2^32 = 58728449 for Dilithium q = 8380417
    Return 58728449
End Process

Note:
SHAKE-128 / SHAKE-256 EXTENDABLE OUTPUT FUNCTIONS (FIPS 202 6.2)

We build these directly on the Keccak-f[1600] permutation exported from
sha3.runa. A SHAKE state stores:
  - 200-byte state         (offset 0)
  - 200-byte scratch_b     (offset 200)
  - 40-byte  scratch_c     (offset 400)
  - 40-byte  scratch_d     (offset 440)
  - 4 bytes: rate_bytes    (offset 480)
  - 4 bytes: squeeze_pos   (offset 484)
  - 4 bytes: absorb_done   (offset 488)
  - 4 bytes: padding_byte  (offset 492; 0x1F for SHAKE, 0x06 for SHA-3)
Total: 496 bytes per state
:End Note

Process called "shake_state_size" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the byte size of a SHAKE incremental state structure so callers
    can pre-allocate scratch from an arena. Layout documented above.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Constant 496 covering 200 + 200 + 40 + 40 + 16 trailing book-keeping
    integers.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant return.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Public layout parameter.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return 496
End Process

Process called "shake_zero_state" takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Zeroes the 200-byte permutation state. Called by shake_init for both
    SHAKE128 and SHAKE256.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Byte-by-byte clear so we do not assume any platform memset alignment.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    O(200); negligible vs Keccak-f cost.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    No secret data on entry.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 200:
        Memory.memory_set_byte(state, i, 0)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "shake_init" takes state_block as Integer, rate_bytes as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Initialises a SHAKE incremental state. The state block must be 496 bytes
    (shake_state_size). rate_bytes is 168 for SHAKE-128 (capacity 256 bits)
    and 136 for SHAKE-256 (capacity 512 bits) per FIPS 202 6.2.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Zeros the 200-byte permutation state, sets rate and metadata.
    Padding byte 0x1F is the SHAKE domain separator (FIPS 202 6.2).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    O(200) byte writes plus a few integer stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    No secret material consumed by init itself.
    @End Security_Scope
    proc shake_zero_state with state_block
    Memory.memory_set_int32(state_block, 480, rate_bytes)
    Memory.memory_set_int32(state_block, 484, 0)
    Memory.memory_set_int32(state_block, 488, 0)
    Memory.memory_set_int32(state_block, 492, 31)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "shake128_init" takes state_block as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Initialises SHAKE-128 with rate 168 bytes.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Calls shake_init with rate_bytes = 168.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) wrapper.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Public parameter setup.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return proc shake_init with state_block, 168
End Process

Process called "shake256_init" takes state_block as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Initialises SHAKE-256 with rate 136 bytes.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Calls shake_init with rate_bytes = 136.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) wrapper.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Public parameter setup.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return proc shake_init with state_block, 136
End Process

Process called "shake_absorb" takes state_block as Integer, data as Integer, data_length as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Absorbs additional input into a SHAKE state. Uses the squeeze_pos field
    as the current absorb offset within the rate prior to the first squeeze.
    Once absorb_done flag flips, further absorb is a programming error and
    is silently ignored to keep the API constant-time.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    XOR each byte into state offset (squeeze_pos % rate). Whenever the
    position hits rate_bytes, run keccak_f1600 and reset the position to 0.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Cost dominated by the underlying Keccak permutation invocations.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Input bytes may be secret. Loop trip count depends on data_length, which
    is a PUBLIC parameter (key/seed/material lengths are fixed by the FIPS
    spec).
    @End Security_Scope
    Let rate_bytes be Memory.memory_get_int32(state_block, 480)
    Let pos be Memory.memory_get_int32(state_block, 484)
    Let absorb_done be Memory.memory_get_int32(state_block, 488)
    If absorb_done is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let state be state_block
    Let scratch_b be state_block plus 200
    Let scratch_c be state_block plus 400
    Let scratch_d be state_block plus 440
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than data_length:
        Let src_b be Memory.memory_get_byte(data, i)
        Let st_b be Memory.memory_get_byte(state, pos)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(state, pos, st_b bitwise_xor src_b)
        Set pos to pos plus 1
        If pos is equal to rate_bytes:
            proc keccak_f1600 from Sha3 with state, scratch_b, scratch_c, scratch_d
            Set pos to 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Memory.memory_set_int32(state_block, 484, pos)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "shake_finalize" takes state_block as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Applies the SHAKE domain separator 0x1F at the current absorb position
    and the closing 0x80 at rate-1, then runs Keccak-f to produce the first
    output block. Sets absorb_done = 1 and resets squeeze_pos = 0.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    FIPS 202 SHAKE padding pad10*1 with domain separator 0x1F.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One Keccak permutation.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time (no data branches).
    @End Security_Scope
    Let rate_bytes be Memory.memory_get_int32(state_block, 480)
    Let pos be Memory.memory_get_int32(state_block, 484)
    Let state be state_block
    Let scratch_b be state_block plus 200
    Let scratch_c be state_block plus 400
    Let scratch_d be state_block plus 440
    Let pad_b be Memory.memory_get_byte(state, pos)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(state, pos, pad_b bitwise_xor 31)
    Let tail_idx be rate_bytes minus 1
    Let tail_b be Memory.memory_get_byte(state, tail_idx)
    Memory.memory_set_byte(state, tail_idx, tail_b bitwise_xor 128)
    proc keccak_f1600 from Sha3 with state, scratch_b, scratch_c, scratch_d
    Memory.memory_set_int32(state_block, 484, 0)
    Memory.memory_set_int32(state_block, 488, 1)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "shake_squeeze" takes state_block as Integer, output as Integer, output_length as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Streams output_length bytes out of the SHAKE state. If absorb_done is
    not yet set, automatically finalizes the absorb phase first (matching the
    one-shot SHAKE-hash convention). Squeezes one block at a time, calling
    keccak_f1600 when the per-block window is exhausted.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    The pos field stores the squeeze position within the current rate block
    (0..rate_bytes-1). When pos reaches rate_bytes a fresh permutation is
    applied.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Memory copies are byte-level for portability; per-output-byte cost is
    dominated by the underlying Keccak when output_length > rate_bytes.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: every loop iteration takes the same path.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let absorb_done be Memory.memory_get_int32(state_block, 488)
    If absorb_done is equal to 0:
        proc shake_finalize with state_block
    End If
    Let rate_bytes be Memory.memory_get_int32(state_block, 480)
    Let pos be Memory.memory_get_int32(state_block, 484)
    Let state be state_block
    Let scratch_b be state_block plus 200
    Let scratch_c be state_block plus 400
    Let scratch_d be state_block plus 440
    Let written be 0
    While written is less than output_length:
        If pos is equal to rate_bytes:
            proc keccak_f1600 from Sha3 with state, scratch_b, scratch_c, scratch_d
            Set pos to 0
        End If
        Let st_b2 be Memory.memory_get_byte(state, pos)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(output, written, st_b2)
        Set pos to pos plus 1
        Set written to written plus 1
    End While
    Memory.memory_set_int32(state_block, 484, pos)
    Return output_length
End Process

Process called "shake128" takes arena as Integer, input as Integer, input_length as Integer, output as Integer, output_length as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    One-shot SHAKE-128 convenience entry point: absorb, finalize, squeeze.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Allocates a 496-byte state from the arena, runs the three SHAKE phases,
    returns output_length on success.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Caller should reuse incremental shake_init/absorb/squeeze when streaming
    many small messages with the same prefix.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Arena memory is not zeroed on release. Caller responsible for clearing
    if input is sensitive.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let st be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, 496)
    If st is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc shake128_init with st
    proc shake_absorb with st, input, input_length
    proc shake_finalize with st
    Return proc shake_squeeze with st, output, output_length
End Process

Process called "shake256" takes arena as Integer, input as Integer, input_length as Integer, output as Integer, output_length as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    One-shot SHAKE-256 convenience entry point.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Same structure as shake128, with rate 136.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Reuse incremental API when streaming many small messages.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    See shake128 note on arena residue.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let st2 be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, 496)
    If st2 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc shake256_init with st2
    proc shake_absorb with st2, input, input_length
    proc shake_finalize with st2
    Return proc shake_squeeze with st2, output, output_length
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MODULAR REDUCTION HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "ntt_asr64" takes value as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Constant-time arithmetic (sign-extending) right shift by n bits,
    1 <= n <= 63. Runa's `shifted right by` is logical (unsigned, shrq);
    Barrett and Montgomery reductions feed signed values (post-multiply
    differences) into the rounding shift and require sign-extension so
    that negative inputs land at floor(value / 2^n) rather than the
    truncate-toward-zero behaviour of `divided by`.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Branchless sign-extend formula:
      sign_extract = value >> 63 (logical) ; 0 or 1
      fill_word    = 0 - sign_extract        ; 0 or -1
      logical_part = value >> n (logical)
      sign_ext     = fill_word << (64 - n)   ; top n bits if neg
      return logical_part | sign_ext
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Five integer ALU ops per call. Shift amount n is a public Barrett /
    Montgomery constant at every call site, so 64-minus-n is also a
    constant.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time over value. Used in NTT reductions of secret-dependent
    coefficients; absence of value-driven branches is required for
    side-channel resistance.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let sign_extract be value shifted right by 63
    Let fill_word be 0 minus sign_extract
    Let logical_part be value shifted right by n
    Let shift_left_amount be 64 minus n
    Let sign_extension be fill_word shifted left by shift_left_amount
    Return logical_part bitwise_or sign_extension
End Process

Process called "barrett_reduce_kyber" takes a as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Barrett reduction modulo Kyber q = 3329. Maps any 32-bit signed input
    range into the canonical representative in [0, q-1]. Used after operations
    that may produce results in [0, q^2) or similar.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Constant v = floor(2^26 / q) = 20159. t = (v*a + 2^25) >> 26. r = a - t*q.
    Adjust by adding q if r is negative (constant-time mask).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Branch-free except for the final cmov-style mask which the runa codegen
    keeps as plain arithmetic.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: no data-dependent branch on coefficient value.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let q be 3329
    Let v be 20159
    Let t be a multiplied by v plus 33554432
    Set t to ntt_asr64(t, 26)
    Let r be a minus t multiplied by q
    Let mask be 0
    If r is less than 0:
        Set mask to q
    End If
    Return r plus mask
End Process

Process called "montgomery_reduce_kyber" takes a as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Montgomery reduction modulo Kyber q. Converts a 32-bit value t (= a*R mod q)
    back into the standard representative. R = 2^16; q*qinv = -1 mod 2^16
    where qinv = 62209.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    u = (a * qinv) mod 2^16, interpreted as a signed 16-bit value via
    extension. Result = (a - u*q) >> 16, then add q if negative.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single multiplication chain with no branches except the final mask.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let q be 3329
    Let qinv be 62209
    Let u be a multiplied by qinv bitwise_and 65535
    If u is greater than or equal to 32768:
        Set u to u minus 65536
    End If
    Let r be a minus u multiplied by q
    Set r to ntt_asr64(r, 16)
    If r is less than 0:
        Set r to r plus q
    End If
    Return r
End Process

Process called "barrett_reduce_dilithium" takes a as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Barrett reduction modulo Dilithium q = 8380417. Used to normalise NTT
    multiplication outputs into [0, q-1].
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    For 32-bit inputs we use the standard Barrett constant chain. We pick
    v = floor(2^45 / q) which keeps |v*a| within 64-bit range.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Uses 64-bit multiplication; runa Integer is 64-bit.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let q be 8380417
    Let v be 4198410
    Let t be a multiplied by v
    Set t to ntt_asr64(t, 45)
    Let r be a minus t multiplied by q
    If r is less than 0:
        Set r to r plus q
    End If
    If r is greater than or equal to q:
        Set r to r minus q
    End If
    Return r
End Process

Process called "montgomery_reduce_dilithium" takes a as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Montgomery reduction modulo Dilithium q. Converts t = a*R mod q with
    R = 2^32. qinv = 58728449 satisfies q*qinv = -1 mod 2^32.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    u = (a * qinv) mod 2^32 as signed; result = (a - u*q) >> 32.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single 64x64 multiplication.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let q be 8380417
    Let qinv be 58728449
    Let mask32 be 4294967295
    Let u be a multiplied by qinv bitwise_and mask32
    If u is greater than or equal to 2147483648:
        Set u to u minus 4294967296
    End If
    Let r be a minus u multiplied by q
    Set r to ntt_asr64(r, 32)
    Return r
End Process

Note:
KYBER ZETA (twiddle) TABLE

Precomputed table of 128 zeta values for the FIPS 203 NTT. These are
powers of zeta = 17 (the primitive 256-th root of unity mod 3329), stored
in bit-reversed order, in Montgomery form (multiplied by R = 2^16 mod q).
Values taken directly from the reference Kyber implementation
(libcrux/PQClean reference).
:End Note

Process called "kyber_zeta" takes index as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the index-th Kyber twiddle in Montgomery domain. Indexed 0..127.
    Table from FIPS 203 Annex / pq-crystals reference.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Cascaded If ladder. Constant-time across all entries because each If
    arm has identical cost (a comparison and a literal return).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Caller-side: callers within the NTT inner loop fetch sequentially, so the
    branch predictor sees a predictable pattern.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Index is loop-induction-variable derived from public parameters.
    @End Security_Scope
    If index is equal to 0:
        Return negative_one_for_zero()
    End If
    If index is equal to 1:
        Return negative_758()
    End If
    If index is equal to 2:
        Return negative_359()
    End If
    If index is equal to 3:
        Return negative_1517()
    End If
    If index is equal to 4:
        Return 1493
    End If
    If index is equal to 5:
        Return 1422
    End If
    If index is equal to 6:
        Return 287
    End If
    If index is equal to 7:
        Return 202
    End If
    If index is equal to 8:
        Return negative_171()
    End If
    If index is equal to 9:
        Return 622
    End If
    If index is equal to 10:
        Return 1577
    End If
    If index is equal to 11:
        Return 182
    End If
    If index is equal to 12:
        Return 962
    End If
    If index is equal to 13:
        Return negative_1202()
    End If
    If index is equal to 14:
        Return negative_1474()
    End If
    If index is equal to 15:
        Return 1468
    End If
